    content:
      "Devon sent back the draft I'd worked on for most of Tuesday with a single line: \"Think this needs another pass — some of the framing feels off.\" That was the whole message. No specifics, no examples of what felt off, just that. I read it three times and then closed the window and went to make more coffee even though I'd already had too much.\n\nStanding at the counter waiting for it to brew, I heard the voice start up. Not gently.\n\n*You wrote forty-five minutes of thinking into that draft and they can't even tell you what's wrong with it. Because what's wrong with it is you. You don't actually know how to frame things, you just think you do. You've been faking the confident version this whole time and now someone read it carefully enough to notice.*\n\nIt went on like that for a little while. I stood there with the mug and just let it go.\n\nThe thing is, if Devon had sent that message to someone else, and that someone else had come to me upset about it, I would have said: that feedback is too vague to be useful, that's not on you. I would have meant it. I would have said, send back a note asking for specifics, that's a completely reasonable thing to do, you're not being difficult. I would have been calm and certain about it.\n\nFor myself the response is: you've been faking the confident version this whole time.\n\nThere's a disproportion there that I can see when I write it out. I can see it clearly and it doesn't fully change anything.\n\nI think what happened is that the Devon message landed on top of something that was already there. The Mei presentation from last week went fine — the room was small, people were engaged, she caught me afterward and said good job — but I've been waiting for something to go wrong ever since. Like the good outcome was a temporary condition and the real verdict was still pending. Devon's message felt like the verdict arriving.\n\nWhich is a lot of weight to put on \"think this needs another pass.\"\n\nI went back to my desk and read the draft again, trying to see it the way someone else would. And honestly? There was a section in the middle where I'd gotten loose with the through-line, where I was sort of gesturing at a point rather than making it. Devon wasn't wrong. The framing there was soft.\n\nAnd then the voice came back but differently this time, almost pleased with itself: *See. There it is. You even knew while you were writing it and you sent it anyway because you wanted to be done.*\n\nThat part landed harder than the first round. Because it had some truth in it. I did feel the soft spot while I was writing and I talked myself past it, told myself it was close enough, that I was overthinking.\n\nI wouldn't say that to anyone, either. The *see, there it is, you knew.* I would never. If a friend told me they'd submitted something with a section they weren't sure about, I would not say: and you did it anyway because you just wanted to be finished. Like it was a character flaw to want to be done with something, like everyone doesn't do that every day.\n\nThere's something in me that keeps very careful records. Every time I cut a corner, every moment I glossed over something, every four-second yes in a hallway — it's all in there, indexed, ready to surface at the first available crack.\n\nSam was in the other room when I got home. I came in, put my bag down, and Sam looked up and said you seem tense. I said I'm just tired. Which is a kind of yes that comes out of me automatically — sure, tired, fine, nothing to work through here. Easier than explaining that I spent part of the afternoon in a low-grade argument with myself over a draft that I've since revised and sent back.\n\nI did revise it, by the way. I tightened the middle section, made the through-line cleaner, sent it back with a note asking Devon to flag anything still feeling off. Devon replied within ten minutes: \"Yes, much better.\" That was it.\n\nSo the thing that set off twenty minutes of *you've been faking it* was a problem I identified, fixed, and resolved before dinner. And somewhere in there is the part that I can't quite get ahold of — why the voice doesn't scale with the actual size of the situation. A loose paragraph in a draft. A fixable thing. And what showed up was the whole case for the prosecution.\n\nI made dinner and it was fine. We talked about something else. The draft is done. But I keep thinking about that voice standing at the counter and just going, and how certain it sounded, and how I didn't push back on it once.",
